'''Louise Hedwig Anna Wilhelmine Piëch''' (née '''Porsche'''; 29 August 1904, in [[Wiener Neustadt]] – 10 February 1999, in [[Zell am See]]) was the daughter of automotive pioneer [[Ferdinand Porsche]]. In 1928, she married [[Anton Piëch]],<ref>[http://www.porsche-holding.at/en/history/luise_pieech_and_ferry_porsche/a_brand_emerges/ Porsche Holding] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113092311/http://www.porsche-holding.at/en/history/luise_pieech_and_ferry_porsche/a_brand_emerges |date=2010-11-13 }} Retrieved 4 October 2010.</ref> a lawyer from [[Vienna]] who from 1941 to 1945 led the [[KdF-Wagen]] ([[Volkswagen]]) factory in [[KdF-Stadt]] (present day [[Wolfsburg]]).
The couple had four children: [[Ernst Piëch|Ernst]], [[Louise Daxer-Piëch|Louise]], [[Ferdinand Piëch|Ferdinand]] and [[Hans Michel Piëch|Hans-Michel]].
When her husband died in 1952, the [[Austria]]n businesswoman imported [[Porsche]] and Volkswagen cars to Austria.
When her son Ferdinand was in charge of Porsche's sports car racing program in the late 1960s, a second works team was set up, called [[Porsche Salzburg]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=MMkYE93ZaScC&pg=PT19&dq=Louise+Pi%C3%ABch&hl=en&ei=EkyqTIuxLpOcsQPrwcm2Aw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=Louise%20Pi%C3%ABch&f=falsePorsche 908: The Long Distance Runner - Google Books - p. 19] Retrieved 4 October 2010.</ref> One of their cars scored the marque's first overall win at [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] in 1970.<ref>[http://www.formula2.net/1970.htm Le Mans Register - 1970] Retrieved 4 October 2010.</ref>
