'''Njabulo Mabuza''' is a [[Swaziland|Swazi]] businessman and politician. He is the member of parliament for [[Kubuta|Khubuta]] [[inkhundla]] for the term from 2013 until 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.times.co.sz/news/92300-myeza-wants-khubuta-mp%E2%80%99s-election-nullified.html|title=Times Of Swaziland|website=www.times.co.sz|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref> He was the Minister for Health and Social Welfare and MP for [[Kubuta|Khubuta]] constituency for two terms before being replaced by [[Charles Myeza]].
==Career== Mabuza was originally a bus operator, running Mdumiseni Bus Service.<ref name="TS">{{cite web|url=http://swazielections.blogspot.co.uk/2008/09/swazi-poll-winners-and-losers.html|title=SWAZI POLL - WINNERS AND LOSERS:Njabulo Mabuza left scratching his head|publisher=''Times Sunday''|date=21 September 2008|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref> Mabuza was once the Chairman of the Public Accounts Committee, which is a parliamentary committee which regulates government spending.
==Minister of Health== Mabuza was a controversial figure during his second term as Minister for Health and Social Welfare which "coincided with the collapse of the health sector in the country" with an acute shortage of drugs and medical facilities.<ref name="TS"/> In 2007, Mabuza banned the media from entering the [[Mbabane Government Hospital]] as criticism mounted.<ref name="Africa2007">{{cite book|title=So this is democracy?: report on media freedom in Southern Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7f8pAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=21 March 2012|year=2007|publisher=[[Media Institute of Southern Africa]]|isbn=978-99916-62-15-2|page=93}}</ref> During his term as minister he "blamed budgetary constraints and "technical problems" for the failure to pay grants to widows and the elderly".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afrol.com/articles/22518|title=Swaziland's parliament goes on 'strike'|publisher=Afrol|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref> In 2011 he was involved in a court case for allegedly failing to pay E200.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.times.co.sz/News/70742.html|title=Njabulo’s appeal struck off after failure to pay E200|publisher=''[[Times of Swaziland]]''|date=17 November 2011|accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>
